properties.Title: Special Weather Statement In Effect
properties.Summary:
Description: More snow on the way to start the week. Total snowfall: generally 10 cm with locally higher amounts possible in areas of heavier snow. Locations: Green Bay - White Bay, Deer Lake - Humber Valley, and Channel - Port aux Basques. Time Frame: tonight until Monday morning. Remarks: Light, fluffy snow will blow around easily in strong easterly winds in the southwest, creating localised blowing snow. It is possible more snowfall warnings may need to be issued. ### Please continue to monitor alerts and forecasts issued by Environment Canada. To report severe weather, send an email to NLstorm@canada.ca or tweet reports using #NLwx.

properties.Title: Freezing Rain Warning In Effect
properties.Summary:
Description: Freezing rain extending along the highways east of Hope. A strong storm system has brought mixed precipitation to the Fraser Valley. Warm air aloft pushes inland tonight and freezing rain is expected for portions of the Coquihalla and the Hope Princeton Highways, near Hope. Freezing rain will extend further inland Sunday morning then transition to rain showers late Sunday morning on the Coquihalla and around noon on the Hope Princeton Highway. ### Surfaces such as highways, roads, walkways and parking lots will become icy, slippery and hazardous. Weather in the mountains can change suddenly resulting in hazardous driving conditions. Road conditions are available at www.drivebc.ca. Please continue to monitor alerts and forecasts issued by Environment Canada. To report severe weather, send an email to BCstorm@canada.ca or tweet reports using #BCStorm.

properties.Title: Snow Squall Watch In Effect
properties.Summary:
Description: Snow squalls possible late this morning. Snow squalls north of the London area early this morning are forecast to continue shifting southward through the morning towards London. If the snow squalls maintain their current intensity, a snow squall warning may be required for the London area. By afternoon, the squalls are forecast to weaken and shift south and west of London. Snowfall accumulations up to 10 cm will be possible as well as localized blowing snow due to strong westerly winds. ### Snow squalls cause weather conditions to vary considerably; changes from clear skies to heavy snow within just a few kilometres are common. Visibility may be suddenly reduced at times in heavy snow. Please continue to monitor alerts and forecasts issued by Environment Canada. To report severe weather, send an email to ONstorm@canada.ca or tweet reports using #ONStorm.

properties.Summary:
Description: Significant snowfall today Total snowfall: 10 to 20 cm, with up to 30 over parts of Victoria County. Maximum wind gusts: 50-70 km/h. Locations: central, northern, and eastern Nova Scotia Time span: today and this evening Remarks: Snow will spread from mainland Nova Scotia to Cape Breton early this morning. properties.Title: Extreme Cold Warning In Effect
properties.Summary:
Description: A period of very cold wind chills is expected. The coldest wind chill values will be between minus 45 and minus 50. Extreme wind chill values will end later this morning as temperatures start to moderate to more seasonal values. ### Extreme cold puts everyone at risk. Risks are greater for young children, older adults, people with chronic illnesses, people working or exercising outdoors, and those without proper shelter. Watch for cold related symptoms: shortness of breath, chest pain, muscle pain and weakness, numbness and colour change in fingers and toes. Extreme cold warnings are issued when very cold temperatures or wind chill creates an elevated risk to health such as frost bite and hypothermia. Please continue to monitor alerts and forecasts issued by Environment Canada. To report severe weather, send an email to SKstorm@canada.ca or tweet reports using #SKStorm.
Expires: 2020-01-20T00:36:22-00:00

properties.Title: Freezing Rain Warning In Effect
properties.Summary:
Description: Freezing rain is expected or occurring. Freezing rain will develop overnight near Chilliwack and Hope. The freezing rain will change to rain early Sunday morning near Chilliwack and early Sunday afternoon near Hope. ### Surfaces such as highways, roads, walkways and parking lots may become icy and slippery. Ice build-up may cause tree branches to break. Please continue to monitor alerts and forecasts issued by Environment Canada. To report severe weather, send an email to BCstorm@canada.ca or tweet reports using #BCStorm.

properties.Title: Snow Squall Warning In Effect
properties.Summary:
Description: Snow squalls this morning. Snow squalls have developed over Lake Huron. The most intense snow squall is currently moving inland near Port Albert but is forecast to shift southward through the morning towards the Goderich and Exeter areas. Snowfall accumulations up to 15 cm will be possible today with these snow squalls. Heavy bursts of snow and significantly reduced visibilities at times can be expected through this morning. Motorists are advised to exercise caution and be prepared for quickly changing driving conditions. ### Snow squalls cause weather conditions to vary considerably; changes from clear skies to heavy snow within just a few kilometres are common. Please continue to monitor alerts and forecasts issued by Environment Canada. To report severe weather, send an email to ONstorm@canada.ca or tweet reports using #ONStorm.
Expires: 2020-01-20T01:00:14-00:00
Originated from CAP Alert: Environment Canada, 2020-01-19T10:47:14-00:00, urn:oid:2.49.0.1.124.3534672964.2020

properties.Title: Winter Storm Warning In Effect
properties.Summary:
Description: Hazardous winter conditions are expected. A strong Pacific storm has arrived with a mix of wintery weather including heavy snow and freezing rain. The freezing rain over northern sections of Squamish will change to rain near midnight. Snow will continue to fall over northern sections of the Sea to Sky with amounts up to 20 cm expected. The snow will change over to freezing rain late Sunday. ### Rapidly accumulating snow will make travel difficult. Visibility may be suddenly reduced at times in heavy snow. Winter storm warnings are issued when multiple types of severe winter weather are expected to occur together. Please continue to monitor alerts and forecasts issued by Environment Canada. To report severe weather, send an email to BCstorm@canada.ca or tweet reports using #BCStorm.
